rom the broadest historical and denominational scope. By examining the works of philosophers and theologians, of poets, painters, and novelists – from Saint Mark to Jacques Derrida and from Erasmus, Loyola, and Milton to Rouault to Andrew Greeley – the essayists seek to answer the question Jesus posed to his disciples: “Who do you say that I am?” and to anticipate the equally contentious query: “How do you say who I am?”The essays together explore the religious imagination through the question of transcendence, using both the age-old Christian imagination and the contemporary world wherein the divisions between religious cultures are less fixed, an age of imaginative permeability where the absence of God is as present as the presence of God.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 03. Jan 2023) 7aRELIGION / Christianity / General.2bisacsh1 aCary, Norman R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChang, Sheng- Tai, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrowley, Paul G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeen Schildgen, Brenda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aD’Costa, Gavin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFranke, William, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreeley, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKristof, Jane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLievestro, Christiaan Theodoor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMormando, Franco, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOakes, Edward T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aParker, Jo Ellen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vo